<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-962-168  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 962 168.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  Dec 11 1989 n249 p23(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Apple readies System 7.0; despite delay, Mac stays ahead inoperating system race.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>McPartlin, John P.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Apple's Macintosh System 7.0 operating system upgrade scheduledfor the 1st or 2nd qtr of 1990 is expected to be stable longbefore IBM's OS/2 Extended Edition will be readily available.andO;Apple promises that System 7.0 will provide major improvementsover the current system, including an increase in virtual memory,which will ease memory-intensive applications.andP;  Featuresanticipated in the upgrade include: font technology with abuilt-in Postscript-like page-description language and a layoutmanager; a more user-friendly Finder; a Database Access Managerenabling linkage to SQL and other databases; a CommunicationsToolbox for standardizing interfaces on communicationsapplications; better multitasking; and the InterapplicationsCommunication Architecture, which handles data and commandexchanges between various Macintosh applications.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (product development).andO;Product:   Apple Macintosh (Microcomputer) (product enhancement)System 7.0 (Operating system) (product development).andO;Topic:     Operating SystemsVirtual MemoryUpgradingCompetitionMicrocomputersSoftware DesignEnhancements.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>